 dominoes: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom collections import defaultdict\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def numEquivDominoPairs(self, dominoes: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        # Use a dictionary to count occurrences of each normalized domino\n        count = defaultdict(int)\n        result = 0\n        \n        for domino in dominoes:\n            # Normalize the domino by sorting the pair\n            normalized = tuple(sorted(domino))\n            # If we have seen this domino before, it can form pairs with all previous occurrences\n            result += count[normalized]\n            # Increment the count of this domino\n            count[normalized] += 1\n        \n        return result\n```\n\nThis solution uses a dictionary to count the occurrences of each normalized domino. By normalizing each domino (i.e., sorting the pair), we ensure that equivalent dominoes are counted together. For each domino, we add the number of times we have seen it before to the result, as each previous occurrence can form a pair with the current domino. We then increment the count of the current domino in the dictionary. This approach efficiently counts all equivalent domino pairs in a single pass through the list.", "estimated_date": 1563667200000}